A little explanation on how figure skating scores work. First of all this video is under the -3 +3 system! You have the technical Element Scores (TES) and artistic part or Program Components Scores (PCS)  in the screen panel you can see only the TES. How TES is evaluated. It has 2 parts: the Base Value (BV) and Grade Of Execution (GOE)  -BV varies according to the element (more difficult element more higher BV)  -GOE varies according on how an element is executed by the judges according the guide lines and can go (inbthis video under the orevious system) from -3 (RED mark)to +3 (GREEN mark) now from -5 to +5. One of the rule is that the same jump CANNOT be repeated, you get only 75% of the BV and Negative GOE (RED)  Now let's see what happened here. Yuzu did a step out in his 4T that was meant in combination with 1EU3S resulting in a Repeated 4T (RED mark) but in under the pressure of an Olympic competition he changed in few seconds the planned sequence 3A2T into 3A1EU3S minimizing the damage of the previous missing scores, isn't he amazingâ€¼ï¸? The second Red mark is the stiff 3Lz landing and having that ankle injured I don't really know how he managed to not fall â€¼ï¸the yellow mark is for the downgrade of the Step Sequence from 4 to 3. Plus  he was leading with a perfect Short Program where he scored 111.86 Sorry for the long comment but hope it helpsâ€¼ï¸ğŸ˜Š

@mhsm8842 You sound like u don't know the rules.

A little explanation on how figure skating scores work. First of all this video is under the -3 +3 system! You have the technical Element Scores (TES) and artistic part or Program Components Scores (PCS)  in the screen panel you can see only the TES. How TES is evaluated. It has 2 parts: the Base Value (BV) and Grade Of Execution (GOE)  -BV varies according to the element (more difficult element more higher BV)  -GOE varies according on how an element is executed by the judges according the guide lines and can go (inbthis video under the orevious system) from -3 (RED mark)to +3 (GREEN mark) now from -5 to +5. One of the rule is that the same jump CANNOT be repeated, you get only 75% of the BV and Negative GOE (RED)  Now let's see what happened here. Yuzu did a step out in his 4T that was meant in combination with 1EU3S resulting in a Repeated 4T (RED mark) but in under the pressure of an Olympic competition he changed in few seconds the planned sequence 3A2T into 3A1EU3S minimizing the damage of the previous missing scores, isn't he amazingâ€¼ï¸? The second Red mark is the stiff 3Lz landing and having that ankle injured I don't really know how he managed to not fall â€¼ï¸the yellow mark is for the downgrade of the Step Sequence from 4 to 3. Sorry for the long comment but hope it helpsâ€¼ï¸ğŸ˜Š

@SarahDixon-tx4zxÂ  No doubt about that. But Hanyu is the most complete skater ever. He has the most variations of difficult spins, most intricate foot work, most difficult entry and exit of big jumps, unique music choices, and the ability to express different genres of music. But most importantly, he has the ability to ignite the feelings and emotions of the audience. Many audiences cried or teared up at the end of some of his performances with quiet music. His greatness lies with how he revolutionised the sports. He was doubted whenever he made a bold choice. Every step that he made was new back then, people only realised it was doable until he perfected it.  For me, John Curry is a great skater that you'll see once in, maybe 30 years? For me, Michelle Kwan and Yuna Kim fall into the same "great skater" category. Their performances are very enjoyable and will certainly be missed. But no one is like Hanyu. He has everything you need and more to be a perfect skater. He is the skater that you'll not see in the next 100 years.  And I haven't even mentioned his personality..

@SarahDixon-tx4zxÂ   Just allow me add one more point. The thing that separates Hanyu from other great skaters in the history (up to 50 years) is how Hanyu transcends figure skating. While skaters like Michelle Kwan, Yuna Kim, John Curry, Brian Boitano, Brian Orser, Yaguddin are great, they were still within the scopes of figure skating. They are the best within the scopes. Â @Myni-7776._Â  Figure skating has 2 performances the short program and the free skate (this video). He was flawless on the short so the 2 mistakes on the free didn't affect his final ranking too much. He scored second on the free but was first overall which is why he won. In figure skating a jump's score has a base value and a grade of exectution ranging from -3 to +3, in the 2 jumps where he messed up, they were fully rotated so he got the base value but got negative grade of execution. The mistakes weren't too costly because he saved the jumps and didn't fall on the ice. In addition, there is another score beside technical score which is the components and he scored very well there which compensated as well. His jump layout was fairly difficult with 4 quads so his base value was also high. All this led to winning the olympic gold medal despite 2 mistakes.

Clapping shouldnâ€™t interrupt your routine because timing your beats and movement literally becomes second nature after practice

clapping as soon as big tech elements (like jumps) are landed is common in FigureSkating, it's kinda "clapping etiquette" so all skaters know this and they learn to deal with it, and afaik is also appreciated, as a way to know the audience sees you and cheers for you. The moments FS audience should absolutely be quiet are, instead, the start of the performance, as skaters take starting position and "get in the zone" to perform, and before a big elements and usually the audience can predict these moments quite well, so you'll notice claps going on and off throughout the skate XD   in Worlds2017 Hope and Legacy you could hear a pin drop before Yuzuru went for the "combo of doom" 4S3T, as it was nicknamed (because Yuzuru had had a bit of a struggle with it till then...not in Helsinki tho! and not in PyeongChang!), people all held their breath and then, as soon as it was done, they roared in joy! in FS it's also common to clap hard as encouragment if something goes wrong with a jump, because it's heartbreaking to see skaters have a bad day so people try to cheer them up after a mistake  In ice shows, on the other hand, I do wish sometimes audience could keep their excitement levels in check till the very end, like Danny Boy in NotteStellata24, it's a program that IMO deserves quiet...(but I also understand the feeling of being overwhemed and not being entirely in control of the sounds you makeğŸ˜…)

I became his fan and a figure skating fan within 10 seconds of watching Yuzuru Hanyu in this performance.....He changed my respect for the sport and became my hero, an inspirational figure to look to and think about when I feel discouraged or need an emotional and psychological uplift.

I  became a Yuzuru Hanyu fan within 10 seconds of watching this performance. Here is a brief summary of my experience.   Speechless! Mind blowing! Indescribable! Historic! Once-in-a-lifetime experience!!! Enthralling!!! Spellbinding! Moving!!! Inspiring!!! Jaw dropping!!! These were the words that came closest to describing the experience of watching Yuzuru Hanyu's SEIMEI program at the 2018 Winter Olympics Games in PyeongChang, South Korea. I have never been one to watch an entire program of ice skating because they are boring. I have seen glimpses of performances of other ice skaters for a few seconds and then moved on to something more interesting...but when I saw Yuzuru Hanyu in this performance I was transformed to the most beautiful life experience in thoughts, emotions, and spirit. I was transfixed, unable to move. Every movement was so precisely executed and so aligned with the music that even a nonexpert eyes could see and feel the dedication, discipline, immense hard work, and love & passion that went into creating the power and emotions depicted in this program. I was moved to tears and had goosebumps as I listened to the powerful & lulling sound of the flute/music and watched Yuzuru glide and dance across the slippery mass of ice on a pair of beautiful blades.  With most athletes, the commentators have to narrate what is done well for the viewers to understand the game, but with Yuzuru an inexperienced pair of eyes or non-expert eyes can tell that he is an extraordinary figure skater, an artistic athlete who delivers a once-in-a-lifetime experience to the viewers through his performances.   Yuzuru's choice of music for this program was courageous because it was out of the norm and the choice of costume was like that of a warrior. Certainly nothing was incidental nor coincidental. Yuzuru Hanyu knew what he wanted and worked in every possible way to bring the power and delicacy of Japanese culture to the world as a figure skater.   After watching this performance (the first time I have ever sat through an entire program of any figure skater), I watched it again and again and again to feel the emotions and the beauty of life again and again and again. Each view also generated more respect and love for this legendary athlete, a figure skater. I also researched Yuzuru Hanyu and his progress toward the culmination of this historic masterpiece.   My research showed that Yuzuru was intentional in bringing not what is stereotypical of a figure skater wanting to win the gold medal at the Olympics Games, but to present Japan's culture. Yuzuru wanted to show that Japan's culture is powerful and delicate at the same time. He worked with top actors to learn about the focus of ancient warrior/lords who were depicted in a Japanese movie, developed movements to depict both power and delicacy of his own culture, chose his costume to create the illusion of a mighty warrior on ice, picked music that is vastly different from the stereotypical music that is expected to be chosen by figure skaters, and worked for years to perfect a performance looking like a powerful, charming, and so, so, so superlatively handsome knight and an artist.   I have never been so powerfully moved internally in my emotions, spirit, and psyche by an athlete's performance before as I have been moved by Yuzuru Hanyu's SEIMEI performance. I was trying hard not to breathe so that I would not miss a single beat of the music and certainly I did not blink my eyes so as not to miss out on any of his movements. It was like watching a deity dance a powerful, liberating dance on ice.   Yuzuru Hanyu's SEIMEI performance will NOT be replicated by anyone ever.  Certainly this Olympics Gold Medalist was a predestined by the Gods and Yuzuru Hanyu was chosen to deliver a program that will not be replicated by anyone else ever.
Only YUZURU HANYU could bring such a wonderful program to us! How amazing he is! GOAT!

Hanyu does not do it for me at all artistry wise but like I said - doubt he cares.

With all due respect, I do not agree about your comment on "wild gesturing between jumps". Those are gestures of Onmyoji, a famous Japanese character that Yuzuru is playing in this performance. Those gestures were well designed and in my opinion these has made the performance complete, with Yuzuru performing it precisely to the beat. It may not be something you can accept easily in the first time if you're not familiar with the culture background. But he certainly didn't short in performing skills comparing to Yuna. After all, "music coming out from his body" is a comment I've heard the most about him from the commentators and I completely agree. I recommend you watch his other performance with western music, eg Chopin Ballade No.1, Notte Stellata, or Parisiene walkways or even Romeo and Juliette (world 2012 in particular), that might make you understand his skating style more. He's famous for the ability to perform all genres of music. I've seen fans who aren't his fans initially because of infamiliar music choice but fall in love with him eventually with his other program. For me my "first love program" of his is Notte stellata. If you love figure skating you certainly cannot miss out this guy!  He is the icon of figure skating.

Ok but actually why did he quit competing? He is only 27.

Â @Aalijah_MatyevnaÂ  the average age of retirement in this sport is 30, Yuzuru retired not because of causes of afe, since he is currently still actively practicing the sport (very recently he started an ice show featuring him and a few of his most famous programs), but because the ISU's new rules for competition do not appreciate the artistic factor that characterizes Yuzuru's stkating, rather giving other stuff more importance. This had been happening for a while, the Federation underscored him, changed rules so he got lower scores and so on, since he is a very important part of this sport and the reason many people got interested in figure skating (myself included) and when he retired, competitions and other figure skaters would get less attention than he did. He holds more than 15 world records, is considered the greatest figure skater of all times and has the love of the public for the way he portrays art and not just pointless spins and turns; so the impact he has had in the sport will remain forever. Â @lorriefinley3129Â  He won't be mistreated any longer by being underscored by the judges to prop up less skilled skaters or being treated like rubbish by his own federation. As a professional athlete now, it's more likely we will be able to see more of his quality skating which has gotten even better after 2018. He's at his peak now and he won't restricted by the rules of this sport which aren't even followed properly by the judges. In August, he even opened a youtube channel HANYU YUZURU (he never had social media before) to make his skating more accessible. Recently, he streamed a live 2-hour practice session called SharePractice in which he skated to his competitive programs like Seimei 3 times, even partly to Hope and Legacy, Tenchi and also threw in White Legend for viewers in the end. As his official professional debut, a few days ago he skated to his latest short program Rondo Capriccioso on 24hrtv (it's available in HD and multi-camera version on youtube now) - this is the most complex short program of all time and his skating was sublime. I only just became a fan of Yuzuru during the Beijing Olympics and have spent the past two months binge watching his past competitions, performances, press conferences, documentaries and fan compilations. What a supreme athlete, all-around artist and beautiful human being -- a rare and pure existence in this chaotic world! It is such a privilege to get to know, support and love him and follow his journey. I have also tried watching other skaters of the current generation, males, females, pairs, but they all come across as ordinary and almost "juvenile" compared to Yuzuru, regardless of the jumps, scores or medals. There is a spiritual quality in Yuzuru's skating which has turned my admiration for him almost into some sort of religious fervor. It is an incredible sensation that I have never experienced and I very much cherish.

Another Olympic game has just started and many of us are watching again this masterpiece. It may not be the best technically performance but this is the best artistically one. The music, the face expression, body move, and the spirit well combined and shined!

For me, the world stops when Yuzuru Hanyu is on the ice.  Not only can he land gorgeous, clean quads and triples axles, but he is a beautiful artistic skater.  I will never forget his "Romeo and Juliet" program (unfortunately, it wasn't clean at the Sochi Olympics).  Jason Brown's artistry is absolutely incredible.  It's what keeps him in the race for a medal, even though he only he only has 1-2 subpar quads, as opposed to 4-6 like Nathan Chen, Hanyu, Vincent Zhou, Boyang Jin, and others.  Brown's "Schindler's List" program gives me chills every time, and I was so happy that he brought it back for the Olympic season.

I already fell for him the first time I saw him skating because of his grace and to be honest everything about him actually. But especially this performance, I don't know much about FS I simply love watching and nothing more, but in my perspective I think that the way he had mistakes, as a skater in olympics with an injured ankle, that made this performance perfect for me. I honestly think if he didn't have any mistakes, which would be amazing to watch sure but, if he didn't then it wouldn't mean this much to me. Because I think "perfection" in like scoring and all, is not what this is about to me. All the hard work and pain and happiness and how he can convey all the emotions within minutes is what's really perfect! This performance showed how you fall and get up several times doing something you are passionate about & life in general and that's the real inspiration here! Thank you.

He is having fun, he practice so much that at this point he is just enjoying, thats the key for everything men, what a performance.

Some facts about this routine:  - The movies the song he skated to is a historical drama movies about a real life figure who was known as the master of yin and yang in Japan - He even went to the shrine dedicated to the said figure. The shrine was located in Kyoto, that took ALMOST 10 HOURS of traveling by car from Sendai - He even consulted the actor who portrayed the said figure in the movie, from the looks, the posture, even the hand gesture. - He edited the music by himself, even to the point he pitch shifted a little bit part of the song to fit the 4 m 30 s time limit. - Shae-Lynn Bourne even watched the movies in advance to be able to understand the historical aspects more. - By the time he skated at this olympic, it was more than 2 years since the first time he skated to this.  EDIT : the movie title is Onmyoji (2004)

Honestly, I never really realized exactly how difficult Ice Skating was until a few minutes ago when I started the video. How do they spin so many times and not throw up? Numbers, short program + free program (this one). Of all male skaters he was the best, the higher number, the sum of short program, Chopin (you can watch here on YT Olympic channel too) and Seimei, this one you have just watched.
Every move has points- the quads are so difficult that you get more points for rotating and falling on a quad than for standing up on a triple
He won the short program, he was second in this (long program). In the sum of both he won by more than 10 points.

Also "almost fell" is different from "fell". He did not even touch his hands on the ice. He did not get the best scores for these two jumps but neither did the worst. In everything there are ratings according to the rules

There's a rule book. If he "Fell" that's 1 point deducted. If he almost fell, the base scores of the jumps are deducted but he still has scores, also the elements like spins and steps, and footwork has some scores too. Even his performance, choreography and skatill skills is scored too. So when combined from his Short Program score, he is leading. Also his top rivals we're also not perfect that time.

Seimei (soundtrack) by Umebayashi

soundtrack from the OnmyÅji movies (which portray character Abe no Seimei, historical character but also part of japanese folklore). Yuzuru chose to name his program SEIMEI, and the reference is also the meaning of the word ("life"), other than the character of Abe no Seimei. The original soundtrack was by Umebayashi, but sound editor Yano edited it (also with changes of tempo, layering different sections and instruments and such) to suit Yuzuru's particular requests and vision (and also to suit a figure skating program). You won't find a piece in the original soundtrack sounding exactly like in this program, though you can definitely recognize the motives.

Let me combine the comments. Dear Hanyu anti Gary, you hate Hanyu but you're always commenting on his videos. Are you a fan in secret? In his 7 year senior career, Chen manage to win only 4 major intl competitions against Hanyu - 4Conts17, Worlds19,21 and GPF2019. He's very overscored and can only jump. He's consistent cause he simplifies transitions from his programs to make jumps easier, both he and his coach Raf openly said this. He's commendable for doing hard jumps with correct technique excluding Axel, but every other component is lacking. FS isn't just jumps. His skating has several objective flaws: poor knee bend, sparse transitions, stiff landings, telegraphed jumps, backwards axel, incorrect sit spins. These should be heavily punished in GOE and PCS, but judges overlook the American's mistakes and underscore the Japanese skater to fabricate undeserved 30 point gaps. The final scores are manipulated by over 20 points thanks to both GOE and PCS. Hanyu and Chen have very close BV since both skate 6 ultra-c elements in the free, but Hanyu delivers complete package programs without simplifying. Hanyu is the best singles skater with no doubt. Accept this truth if you visit his video or go comment your uninformed takes on GibberishSkate.

You should! Yuzuru is truly an inspiration. He's not only the greatest figure skater ever but also a wonderful human. You probably saw this in the comments, but his performance here is proof of his determination and will power: just 3 months prior, he damaged his ankle in an accident, and the injury was so bad that it was unbelievable for him to even skate, let alone win the Olympics! But he persevered, and skating on pain killers, he went on to win his second consecutive gold medal He's been through a lot in his career, actually. Basically there are two kinds of scores that make up the total score. First is the technical one that comes from the technical elements which are jumps, spins and step and choreo sequences. These are graded by the judges during the performance. The second one is the component score which is given on skating skills, transitions, interpretation of the music etc, and itâ€™s added to the technical score after the performance. Now about the change in the technical score, you see the replay of elements in slow motion after the performance right? Thatâ€™s when the technical panel reviews some of the elements to see the mistakes like underrotation, wrong use of edges, missing rotations in spins etc which are sometimes hard to detect during the performance, so if there are mistakes, the score is deducted after the performance. Sometimes it goes up too if the judges change their mind end give higher grades.

yeah that was a loss of control on the landing, though he managed not to put hand down.  That mistake meant a big loss of points in the technical score, because that season rules stated that if one repeats a quad, at least one must be in combo. since that was his second 4T (his first one was the solo 4T in first half of the program), that flawed landing meant that he couldn't attach his planned combo. Because of how his layout was built and of the rules for the free program, that mistake meant he lost at least 10 points overall (for reference, value of a 4T on its own is 10.30). For example a similar mistake on the 3Lz only meant he lost 2-3 points instead (vs a 3Lz base value in the second half of 6.60)

Yuri is based off a number of real-life japanese skaters - the primary one being Tatsuki Machida who is the creator's absolute fave and a lovely skater. You can also find evidence online that the author does hold some degree of dislike for Yuzuru, she would also draw/represent him at times in an unflattering way in comparison to other skaters and irl Yuzu was the one who was beating all the skaters including Machida so that might have contributed to her dislike of him. She wouldn't be the first one, there is a minority of fs fans (who are much much worse and toxic) in japan who have a hate boner for Yuzuru for being the extraordinary athlete he is and for getting all the attention over their favorites. Anyways, the story about these  haters is another story. @GamingWithVlogs In the case of Yuzu, it was a major injury â€” in fact, it was almost a career-ending injury, and something that he continues to deal with to this day. He could not skate at all for months, and was only back at jumping about a week before the Olys; he was on painkillers up until the games because he could not otherwise land without pain. Given how badly Yuzu wanted to win his second Olympic gold he was willing to risk it all for it, and it was his coaches who were very cautious. His ankle was pretty much held together by sheer determination and painkillers.

Hi! There are two programs in figure skating, the short program and the long program. The scores for SP and LP will yhen be added to get the total score. Scoring in both events comprises of TES (technical score) and PCS (program component score). TES comprises of the jumps, spins, and other elements. Each elements have their corresponding scores, and depending on how well a skater executes them they will be given +GOE / - GOE (grade of execution). The technical panel also decides whether to downgrade the jumps or deem them underrotated. PCS on the other hand comprises of skating skills, performance, interpretation, transitions and another criteria that I forgot (sorry). If you want to know the full details, you can visit the ISU website.  I know the judging seems very complicated, it's been the subject of some very heated discussions in every figure skating forums each season. Not to mention on how some judges and tech controllers can be incompetent in applying this in almost every competitions. Sigh...

I'm curious, why China? 2018OWG were in Korea, and while the chinese judge worked hard to prop their own skater (and they've been sanctioned for that... which can't be said for the american judge Lorrie Parker, who actually was the one blatantly underscoring Yuzuru while propping up all 3 US skaters), their scoring of Yuzuru was mostly neutral  During a skate, tech panel can put elements under review (e.g. they can check for rotation, or levels for spins and steps), and later, after a skate has ended, judges can review their scores too (and that's why you can see decimals go up and down too). Then, after tech panel has ended their review and all judges have submitted their scores, the final result is formally announced.  After review, it can happen that score can go down even by more than 10 points, though this wasn't the case  (I don't deny that fudging happens, though, FS is riddled with scandals).

Â @aniruddhajoshi8324Â  , that technique where he balances on one foot with his left hand on the ice is called a Hydroblade. It's somewhat more seen in ice dance and sometimes done in ice shows or ex galas, but Yuzuru has had a Hydroblade in every free skate and ex since 2015. Together with the Ina Bauer, it's his signature choreo sequence. To me, it's really special because I haven't seen many people do it the way he does it, with a right inside edge, and his is also especially memorable because he times it so well with the music! Also, this variation that he does here isn't hard (for him at least,) but he has a more difficult variation where he is nearly lying on the ice, which has led to some mishaps ğŸ˜‚ Anyway, hope this helps!

It's just he makes the difficult elements look easy. It doesn't mean figure skating is not a difficult sport. Making difficult things look easy is more difficult. These all came from hard training and talent, same as many other sports. Also figure skating is a very popular sport in Japan and one of the most popular events in winter olympics.
This is a winter Olympics after all. Cricket is included in Summer Olympics, but I don't think people will play cricket during winter.

It's a sport because it is insanely difficult to jump on ice blades (to put it simply). This is because to perform those jumps they need to create their own force to convert kinetic energy to potential energy. Aside from that, there are no safety equipment or apparel that they wear during these performances, hence if they fall when performing their jumps, the athlete will absorb 100% of the impact. In addition, they also do quadruple, triple or double jumps which are the number they needed to rotate their jumps while being on air.
You need insane leg & core muscles for this, plus decades of hard training. Usually skaters retire in their 20s because their body can't take it anymore. It's one of the toughest sports I know.

it might be hard to believe, but Figure Skating actually was the first winter sport included in the Olympic games XD It is without doubt a weird sport, that mixes athleticism and performance skills so it's quite similar to dance, but for some reasons it evolved as a "sport" instead of as an art form.  Tbh, one might as well think of dancers as athletes too, since they have to go through years of strict training to do what they do. Leaping like they do and landing as gracefully as they do are athletic feats, just like keeping a perfect balance through 40 pirouettes.  The reason why we view dance more as an art while FS became a sport probably has historical reasons: when modern sports stopped being "just" a leisure activity and became what we know now, fully coded sports with their set of rules and official tournements, dance(starting from ballet) was already established as art and just went on like that.  The "ability to skate on ice" wasn't coded as an art yet, so with the advent of modern Olympics it was coded into a sport, instead. A gentlemen's sport, at the beginning, with athleticism being in things like showing off their edging skills and jumping from one spot to the other without ending with their bum on the ice :)  A whole FS routine requires high stamina and huge core strenght: even the most sweet-looking, tiny teenager is absolutely ripped. Some elements, like quadruple jumps and spins, push to the limit of the rotational speed a human body can generate and sustain (with brain and all the other organs being all shaken up and down, left and right). When landing from a quadruple jump, skaters sustain a force up to 10 times their weight... so I hope that there is no doubt that FS is highly demanding, phisically. Further proof of this is the fact that most skaters are already considered past their prime by mid twenties and deveop assorted health problems before their 30s (several stress fractures, back pains, a series of issues consequence of repeated concussions). Heck, many are already battling with chronic pain before thery're 20.  Right now, there is a scoring system (created after the unfamous 2002OWG scandal) that's quite complex and number-based. Skater's performances have a layout that has to be built according to certain requirements and all the tech elements (jumps, spins, steps) get a score based on inherent difficuty and how good the execution was (similarly to gymnastics and diving).  Even for the "performance" side, there are a number of criteria, like depth of edges, ice coverage, use of multidirectional skating that can be assessed, and even measured quantitatively to a degree (you can literally count the changes of direction). The skaters who do the hardest jumps will get points for that, the skaters who can contort themselves into the most difficult spin positions and spin fast and centered will get points for that, those who display superior edging skills through variations in direction and rythm inbetween elements will get points for that and so on. The skaters who get the most points will be those who have such a command on their technical elements that they challenge and execute the hard stuff while making you forget that it's supposed to be hard. By the way, incorporating the highest difficulty into a performance is kind of Hanyu's trademark. Per his words (asked if he saw himself as an athlete or an artist), he views himself as an "artistic athlete", whose performative skills are built upon the strongest technical foundations   I understand why one would think FS can't be "objectively" judged and so it can't be considered a sport. Thing is, it can be objectively judged, with proper tools and training. The real problem is the lack of proper tech equipment and software to objectively assess things like size of jumps, speed, edges, rotations. FS doesn't have the kind of money football or other big sports have, so developing and implementing new technology is hard....but most important, the FS governing body is riddled with corruption and they are allergic to technology and adherence to any kind of standard.  The potential for an objectively-assessed sport is there, but the practice...can be very different.   So, in the end, I might even agree with you and say that FS, maybe, should not be an olympic sport anymore :(  But not because there's something inherently wrong in FS, a reason why it cannot be a sport. It's just that ISU is way too eager to go on with all the merry fudging&politicking that culminated in the 2002OWG scandal and is making a mockery of a judging system that was born to make sure FS still had a place at olympics

Yuzuru is a very expressive skater and maybe you are affected by his emotion here. To provide a background context on how he must feel at the time:  Yuzu's long time dream since childhood is two win Olympics twice. Unlike in other sports, figure skaters tend to retire young and most skaters will go to 2-3 Olympics. Yuzu won his first back in 2014, but 3 months before this Olympic he fell and injured his ankles. One month before PyeongChang, he decided to take painkiller to restart his practice, fully aware that in doing so he might re-injured his ankle so bad that he won't be able to skate again.   In short, he risked it all for this performance and he made it.

It's not easy being a fan of Yuzuru Hanyu.  * He gets injured/ill in almost every season of his senior career. * Insisting to compete while injured/ill.       1. Worlds 2012 - sprained ankle      2. Worlds 2013- flu      3. COC 2014- collission with Han Yan resulting in multitude of injuries.      4. NHK 2014- just 2 weeks after COC thus still unhealed. The only time he was out of the podium since winning GPF 2013.      5. Japan Nationals 2014- competed while oozing blood and pus on the abdomen from a bladder birth defect. Bound his abdomen with bandage and duct tape to avoid ruining his costume. He was rushed to the hospital immediately after the competition.        6. Japan Nationals 2016- He withdraw due to flu.         7. Worlds 2016- He didn't inform his coach that he was experiencing pain on his foot since the beginning of the season. Still competed the whole GP breaking World records back 2 back. He exacerbated his injuries resulting to a meltdown of an FP in Worlds. He was diagnosed with Lisfranc injury. He seriously thought it was the end of his carreer.      8. NHK 2017- went to OP while feverish. Tried jumping quad lutz, fell hard, damaging his ankle ligaments severely. He withdraw from competing.        9. Olympics 2018- After a news blackout for months, he showed up in Korea reassuring everyone that he's now feeling okay to compete. He successfully defended his olympic title, only to announce later that he's still not yet 100% recovered and that he only got through the competition with the help of pain medications. He withdraw from Worlds 2018 to recuperate.         10. Rostelecom Cup 2018-  He reinjured the same ankle while trying to jump the quad loop in practice. Still insisted on competing. Went to podium to get his gold medal wearing crutches.  I really can't believe that I wrote this huge wall of text just to whine about the agony of being a fanyu and list each and every one of Yuzu's propensity in ignoring his well-being. But who am I kidding? Even if he's this reckless, I still support him because he is a good man and I want to see how much farther he can go with his dreams despite having body limitations. He is a huge inspiration.

This sounds a lot like "self-handicapping" -- in psychology, it is a phenomena when youÂ arrange unfavorable circumstances for your important performances so as to maintain self-esteem in case of failure, thereby lowering the pressure on yourself. Self-handicapping is common in athletes, moreover, studies say it is positively related to performance and self-reports of optimal experience in competition... But maybe it's not

@Anna, Iâ€™m not sure that you could â€˜arrangeâ€™ for another skater to collide with you during the warm up, immediately before a competition; or for a bladder birth defect to rupture; or for a lisfranc injury; or a potentially career ending ankle ligament injury; not to mention the many other issues detailed here. Iâ€™m not sure what youâ€™re implying â€¦. that he made these things up as some kind of game-plan ? Baffling !!

Â @henjjs4605Â Â It is not done intentionally. People who self-handicap often struggle themselves with their strategy. Self-handicapping is also not a deliberate game-plan, usually it is done in the form of doing things that you know can hurt you and your performance, bringing some unnecessary risk, something you would not be recommended doing. Such as not following the instructions of your doctors and/or trainers, such as training the unnecessary risky element just before the important competition. Good for you!!! Most people don't know about his injury, so I am impressed by your knowledge! For your information, he is the first male skater to achieve a super slam in his career: he is the Junior GPF champion (2009), Junior World champion (2010), two-time World champion (2014, 2017), double Olympic champion (2014, 2018), GPF champion (2013-2016), and 4CC champion (2020). These are only some of his accomplishments, but I think what makes him truly stand out is how complete he is as a skater. He not only has textbook jumps, but he also has beautiful spins, excellent footwork, phenomenal expression, and so much more. That is something that I admire about him. Most skaters will sacrifice artistry or skating skills for bigger jumps in order to earn higher scores, while others will put aside jumps in order to excel in artistry. But he has unified the two and made them inseparable.  As incredible as he is as an athlete, he is also a very wholesome human. He is respectful and humble, and he always answers interviews wisely and maturely. He is a fighter and survivor: he survived the tsunamis and earthquake that ravaged his home in 2011, and to this day he raises funds to support the repairs and disaster cause. Also, he suffers from asthma. In fact, two weeks before his stunning performance in the 2017 World Championships, he suffered an attack, but he still went on to break yet another world record.   I still remember him as a 17 year old boy, standing upon the podium above Takahashi Daisuke in 2012. He had taken the world by storm and rose to the top above his competitors. But he was not loved for it. The figure skating world was not ready for him, and so that day on the podium, the audience booed him as someone who had stolen the gold from Takahashi Daisuke, their hero. I can only imagine the hurt and betrayal he felt from being beaten down by his own countrymen simply because they loved another more than him. I am awed that he did not crumble under the pressure and anguish, but went on to prove to them that he was the winner.   Sorry for the ramble, but I hope this gives you some insight on Hanyu Yuzuru and shows you how admirable he really is. ğŸ˜Š

Yuzuru is a truly hero, a legendary skater, and a Prince of the ice. He is a born skater.  He survived the 2011 March 11 earthquake and Tsunami, when his family had to sleep in a small space and eat small rice balls distributed by the shelter, unable to go to skate for many days. He yet moved around the country, seeking a chance to skate, not for games but for his own challenges and for his love for the people who suffered from the loss of lives and housing. Even now he continues donating most of his awards and funds received for his championships to his native town every year.  His skating is not just a game but it is his soul, his life, and his love for the people, ice rink, and his family. That is why his skating has everything about a human love, beautiful and great reflection of his being himself.

Yes yuzu is the most famous and best figure skater in the men's singles right now. He is the first man to have broken the 100-point barrier in the men's short program, the 200-point barrier in the men's free skating, and the 300-point barrier in the combined total score. Hanyu is the first Asian figure skater competing in men's singles to win the Olympic gold. Yuzuru Hanyu is the G.O.A.T (The Greatest of All time) of men's figure skating. He is the 2- times olympic champions. He is a two-time Olympic champion (2014, 2018), a two-time World champion (2014, 2017), a four-time Grand Prix Final champion (2013â€“2016), a Four Continents champion (2020), the 2010 World Junior champion, the 2009â€“10 Junior Grand Prix Final champion, and a four-time Japanese national champion (2012â€“2015). He has also medaled at four other World Championships, taking bronze in 2012, and silver in 2015, 2016 and 2019. Upon winning the 2020 Four Continents Championships, Hanyu became the first male singles skater to achieve a Super Slam, having won all major competitions in his senior and junior career. Â @aether9001Â  At two years old, Hanyu was diagnosed with asthma, a condition which slowly improved as he got older. Hanyu began skating at the age of four, following his older sister to the rink.[24][25] His figure skating idol was Evgeni Plushenko.[1] He first competed nationally as a novice skater in the 2004â€“05 season; he skated at the 2004 Japan Novice Championships in the Novice B category, which is the lower of the two categories at the novice level, and won the gold medal in this competition.[26] His home rink then closed due to financial problems, reducing his training time.[25] Nanami Abe became his coach around that time.[25] In the 2006â€“07 season, Hanyu competed at the 2006 Japan Novice Championships in the Novice A category and won the bronze medal.[27] This placement earned him an invitation to compete at the 2006â€“07 Japan Junior Championships, where he placed 7th.[28]  Hanyu's home rink reopened in 2007.[25] He competed at the 2007 Japan Novice Championships in the Novice A category and won the event.[29] He was invited to compete in the 2007â€“08 Japan Junior Championships, where he won the bronze medal

To new fans who want to know more, he is truly a great athlete. I will not name most of his accomplishments here since it is easy to search them up, and he just has that many. But I will inform you that he has broken world records 19 times and that he is considered to be possibly the greatest figure skater of all time. Hanyu Yuzuru is a very complete skater: he can jump perfectly, he has flexibility, musicality, he can execute intricate steps and amazing transitions, and so much more. And furthermore, he is a phenomenal human being. In 2011, at 16 years old, he fled from a collapsing rink. He and his family were victims of the great East Japan Earthquake that occurred that year, and it has left a huge impact on his life. He almost quit skating, and he suffered nightmares from what he had seen. But here he is today, standing at the top of the world, having persevered through it all. His health has also always been an issue for him. He was diagnosed with athsma as a child, and while it has improved considerably, it gives him problems with stamina. He has also suffered career-threatening injuries. In fact, in this competition that we are looking at, he had injured his right ankle, the foot that all his jumps land on. He was skating on painkillers. And yet, he won.   Hanyu Yuzuru has won everything in his career: GPF, World Championships, the Olympics, 4CC, and so much more. Why, he would have even won European Championships, except, you know, he can't because he's Asian. But jokes aside, he has won everything, but he still competes, and it shows how much he wants to push the sport. He wants to land a Quadruple Flip, but even before that, he attempts the Quadruple Axel.   I highly encourage all of you to look more into this man. He is a true inspiration to us all, and I am proud to be his fan.

Google search in 2020!

Generally the point system is split into two: Technicals ( jumps, spins, and step sequence 2:01 to 2:40) and Performance Component Score or PCS.  In the Technical score there is something called the GOE or Grade Of Execution. This is added to the base value of the  jumps. For example, the jump in 0:55 a Quad Salchow was graded a +3 (the highest goe score at that time). The green squares at the top left means the element he did, received a positive GOE. Red means negative.   The PCS is composed of Skating skills, transitions (to a jump), performance, and etc. Basically the things he does in between the jumps. It's graded up to 10.  Then, for the final score, these two (technical and pcs) will be added.

Gautham you have no idea how many people relate to you in the FS twitter verse. Hahhahha.. You're a mood.   Anyway, like Han Yong explained. It's basically  technical elements and presentation. Each technical element like a jump or a spin or a step sequence has a base value.  That base value is given bonuses up to 3 points (Grade of Execution/GOE) if the skater executes them well.  If the execution is shaky or there is a fall, negative GOE is given. And the skater loses some points.    By the end of 2018, a new system of +5/-5 GOE was adopted. Meaning if a skater can perform a jump well and get +5 GOE, they can add up to 50% of the base value. +4 means 40%. +3 means 30%, etc. But if they fall, they can lose up to 50% of the base value. New system.

Â @gautamsrivastav8330Â  What @Kasvini Muniandy means is in figure skating, the technical elements consists of the jumps, spins and step sequence.    First of all, there are 6 different types of jumps, and each jump has a base value-which means they each have been given a certain amount of points that you get should you execute it. So, if you execute it successfully, eg. the Quad Salchow, the first jump as demonstrated by Yuzu, then you get the entire base value+GOE, which is basically extra points added to the base value.     On the other hand, eg. Yuzu's Triple Lutz, the last jump at the end of the program, which was landed shakily, would have received the base value of the jump, but the GOE, the bonus points, would not be added. Instead, the GOE would minus the base value as a result of executing a jump, but not perfectly done. So Yuzu's Triple Lutz had a base value of 6.60, but he got -1.10 GOE, meaning his score for the jump was 5.50. (Hope this is clear? It's a bit hard to understand, I myself learned through other helpful fans:)   *At that time, the system of GOE was that +3 GOE was the maximum added bonus points and -3 GOE was the maximum minus points.

While the implication that he could still phone it in and deliver a winning performance at the Olympics is flattering in and of itself, I'm afraid making half-hearted effort isn't something he does. And even if it were, he most definitely isn't doing it here because he is essentially skating on 1.5 legs.  So while he did skate with a handicap, he had to put everything and then some  into this performance precisely because of that. That he still managed to remain poised enough that you're not seeing the "energy" in it, is testament of his skill. It's there, though. Perhaps not the outward kind you're expecting but there's plenty of energy in this performance. You'd see it, too, if you really looked at it properly enough.

When it comes to competition I think all athletes are extremely concentrated, there's no room for extra emotion. After all, both choreographic elements and technical elements need massive level of control in order to be executed accurately, otherwise athletes risk their safety and quality. In fact you can see how stressful it is in this performance, when only after having completed all his jumping passes did Yuzuru showed his relief and excitement during the choreographic sequence.  They should be more relaxed during exhibitions and ice shows, if that's what you're looking for.

Scoring is extremely difficult to explain to someone who doesn't know anything. Performance scores are added components. Skating skills, transitions, performance, interpretation and composition. The errors were not serious - a fall would have been so it did not or should not have affected the scores much. He suffered in the technical scores for the errors.

Â @subidubiduda5293Â  ooh Thanks so much for answering. I just learned about this guy a couple days ago and have been mesmerized. I just didn't understand how "deductions" could be 0 and thought that meant that the judges were giving him a perfect score!

No. You have to collect the scores. Every elements have their own points according to the level of difficulty like for ex. a quad jump would have a higher base value than a triple jump bcs of extra rotation. And every other elements such as spins and step sequence has their own base value. And then, we have the GOE or grade of execution to score how good they could execute those elements. All of these are only under the TES (total element score) value which is for elements and we have another scoring for components or the performance side which include skating skills, transitions, performance, compositions, interpretations and choreography.   As for Yuzuru here, he still got the marks for the jumps as he still completed the required rotation to get the full base value of the jump but he was being deducted on the GOE side bcs they aren't perfect as you can see. If he fell, then that's another story. As you can see, he's one of those skaters who can get high scores on both TES and PCS side as he have difficult elements in his program whilst also a very good performer. Hope that helps

Look at the rulebook. Look at the criteria for goe, see how many of those are the jumps able to tick off. Let me make it simple for you, empty program where most of what you do is crossovers (to gain speed) and jump, of course you land your jump. Programs with content between jumps, where you add difficulties with transitions, where you show more than just the basics, that's how you compete as an elite athlete. As for difficulties, among the jumps Yuzu have one more 3A. Just saying ;)

Sally Vee i think the fact that many people (even Yuzuru himself!) think he needs to up his difficulty to beat Nathan is probably one of the biggest failures of figure skating judging this sport has seen. People don't actually realize that from a base value perspective Nate and Yuzu are pretty similar, with Yuzu's combos being harder but Nate having a wider arsenal of quads. However, Nathan's GOEs being inflated, UR calls not being consistently made, and the lack of PC gap despite a pretty noticeable difference in transitions (and others, but TR is a lot less up to subjective interpretation), not to mention Nathan is backed by a very powerful SU that is desperate to get the sport back on the maps for Americans, all present a pretty compelling argument for why long-time fans of figure skating are reasonably upset

Worlds and GPF 2019 were a mess. The placements were correct, but the margin between their scores? Unbelievable, almost. Hanyu messed up, yes, and Nathan Chen did not, which is why he is the rightful winner. Congratulations to him! However, the judges sometimes (often) seem to close the rulebooks when he and Hanyu skate. Nathan Chen has textbook jumps, for sure, but he does not have everything the way Hanyu does. So how come he surpassed him in PCS???? Technically, it was an amazing program, if you ignore steps and transitions, but in what way was it better than Hanyu in components? Hanyu was not perfect technically, but it always stuns me how the judges can give him anything less than 99.00 in PCS.   Sometimes I wonder how this affects Hanyu Yuzuru mentally and emotionally. He knows what they do to him. It must, therefore be a burdening thought, stepping onto the ice thinking, "No matter what I do, they will not award me fully." I wish it wasn't this way, but in a sense I think it provides motivation to Hanyu. He will strive harder to present cleanly. No, even more, he will work towards perfection.  He will give them something that is so flawless that even they or anyone else could not deny it. He will show them something that will cause them to helplessly acknowledge, "This is the masterpiece. Here is something that must receive perfect scores, and nothing less. He is the winner."   I wish it weren't this way, but I believe in him. short answer: there are two segments of competition, in the first (SP) he was the most brilliant, in the secons (this) he was brilliant enough. He did the best combination of programs, got the highest overall score, and won.  Longer answer: the mistakes were not "that many", nor the most serious under the current judging system. He only did one minor mistake (a step out on last jump) and a bigger mistake on the second quad toe... "bigger" not because technically worse but because 1)it prevented him from attaching the other planned jump to make a combination and 2) rules state that if you repeat a jump, one must be in combination, and if it's not in coombination you lose points. He was repeatig the quad toe, so in the end that step out made him lose around 10 points, much more than the step out on the last jump).   Still, he didn't fall, didn't UR, didn't pop. He delivered everything else with the highest quality (even got max score possible on the first two jumps, the only man in this competition to do so). The other skaters had 1) overall more mistakes (or more serios mistakes) or 2) less difficult content or 3) what they executed was much lower quality. Difficulty of content, quality of delivery all factor in the final score, so don't be surprised that cleaner programs were scored lower.  If you want details, on ISU website you can find complete scoresheet with the break down of the scores that every single skater received on every single elements by each of the 9 judges. The rest is math.

We live in the U.S. Since we are immigrants from China, my wife started paying attention to Nathan Chen before Olympics and wanted him to win the gold medal in PyeongChang. Nathan failed in short program and then did great in free program. Nathan only got 4th place. My wife only watched Nathan's performance and wasn't happy about it. She thought Nathan is the best player and should have won gold medal if everything is "normal". I said "Watch Hanyu's performance and tell me what you think". Next day, she shook her head and told me "Hanyu is too good and Nathan has nothing to complain".  Considering the hostile feeling between China and Japan due to history, it is very uncommon to see such a lot of chinese people support a Japanese athlete. Chinese national TV commentors used nearly goosebumping words to compliment him.... But true, Hanyu is so great.

Scores in the corner shows the current skater who skates on ice (in this video yuzuru from Japan) and the skater who ranked 1st at the moment (Boyang frm China). The score kept changing was yuzuru's technical score (includes jumps, spins, step sequence, choreo sequence) because he's on the ice skating.  If I'm not wrong yellow means under review, it may be the level of the element was under reviewed because not enough for requirement, i.e spin level 4 but not enough revolution so it became level 3 or less. And the final scoring was a total from Technical (TES) and Program component score (PCS).

@MizukiUkitakeadding to  @BlueFlame   there is a technical panel that calls the number of rotations of jumps and the type of jumps, the level for step sequence (type, number and direction of steps and turns) and level for spins (changes of positions, changes of edges, number of revolutions...). Their calls decide the part of the score that's called base value (BV).   there is also a separate panel of judges in charge of evaluing the quality of every elements (GOE) and judging the program as a whole, rating things like how well skaters glide, how well they move to the music, complexity of the program (PCS). Sometimes commentators make it sound as if PCS are only about "artistry" but some components are still quite technical and are related to the very core of "figure skating", "drawing figures on the ice using skates", so the pure "use of the blade on the ice".    what you see in the box, increasing during the skate, are TES (BV+GOE). the green means currently that element has positive goe, yellow marked for review, red negative goe (in this program for example the 3Lz was rotated but had a step out so it got its BV but negative GOE and the tiny square is red).PCS are displayed only when official scores are announced.   The reason why you see fluctuations of TES even after a program has ended is because: 1) BV can change. Some things are hard to tell live even for specialists, so they mark some elements for review after the program is finished  Sometimes they confirm their first call, sometimes not.  e.g. if you see the TES drop of several points at once, a safe bet is that the tech panel has called some underrotations on jumps.  some smaller changes are due to levels of spins and steps  2) judges can replay elements too (every element they want, not only those marked by tech panel) and they are allowed to change their scores before submitting them.  Usually the continuous small fluctuations (decimals) happen when judges change GOE (you see the average GOE from all judges, so if only one judge change a +1 for a +2 the average won't change that much) Also, when tech panels call things like underrotations, judges are also supposed to adjust their GOE accordingly.   by the way, if you watch other vids from other competitions, you'll see a different TES box with many more info, like the name of every element as the skaters execute it and the goe on that single element, plus the total TES.It's helpful if you want to learn to tell jumps apart.

because this is the no-commentary version from Olympic Channel, so the only voice is from the announcer in the arena, basically all you hear is what poeple in the arena heard. Usually broadcasters add their own commentary on the original video feed (you'll see every broadcaster has same footage, though occasionally for some competitions Japan TV might have different camera angle and for Olympics NBC had different footage from everyone else)if you prefer to have a comment during the performance with all elements called & insights, there are many videos (just e.g. add NBC or NBCSN or BBC or ESP and so on in the search bar next to the name of skater...though some videos might have been taken down due to the recent purge of several FS channels)Personally, while I like the different opinions from different commatators and sometimes there are interesting insights, I prefer the no-commentary when rewatching, no bias due to people commentating, no distraction from the performance (also, sometimes I happen to disagree with the comments so better not being forced to listen and roll my eys everytime LOL). I also like commetaries like Ted Barton's in JGP series, where he only talks after the performance, during replays Though, some commentaries are epic and worth rewathcing in their own right :)

I totally understand what you mean (and agree with it) but Yuzu actually was playing it safe here. : P  He had a more ambitious program planned (with different jumps) at the start of the season, before his injury in November 2017. But yes, for someone coming off a major injury and skating on painkillers, everything was risky and he pulled it off beautifully. He was also on painkillers during his on-ice training for about a month before the Olympics. He decided he had to train with painkillers, even though there was a chance it could worsen his condition in the long run, and that if he didn't do so there was no chance he would have been ready for the Olympics in time. : (    I'm so glad it paid off.

The score that goes up and down is the technical score. All elements have base value and grade of execution (GOE). GOE can be either positive, that means a skater gets additional points for a good executed element, or negative which some points are taken. If skater falls, they receive also one point deduction, but from the third one, falls are more costly. The technical score always fluctuates and the definitive TES score seen in KIss&Cry  can be very different from the one seen after finishing a program because elements can be taken under revision to check if there was an underrotation or an unclear edge on a jump. Those are basics, there are more rules like Zayak rule which affected his score here :)

maybe because in GPF2015 Yuzuru was triumphant but more 'in control', while this performance is filled with fierceness and unbridled emotions that literally explode in the choreo seq (to me it's his best Seimei choreo seq ever). It could be argued that in GPF he was more "in character", but this, despite the technical flaws, is the most confident Seimei, imo, with the quiet control of the first half that builds and builds and becomes a storm (chinese commentary was so on point)  also in these years Yuzuru's skating has improved a lot. Not that before he was bad, not at all, but it looks like he magically upgrades his skating skills everytime we see him...and with all his injuries he's often been kind of forced to long periods of stroking training only, as his jump training was on hiatus :'(   so, deeper edges, more sharpness and command in his every move (stsq lv3 notwhistanding LOL).   The 4T he does in first half here is among my all-time favourite jumps ever, starting from all the transitions and choreography leading in (tbh starting form the 4S, there is no interruption in the choreo), to the jump itself, so smooth and effortless and with so much spped out (and the way he holds his back and free leg  <3<3<3 you can see the utter CONTROL he has, as if there was no chance in hell that jump could go wrong) to the following choreo into 3F into camel spin. While that...kinda crane-pose he does after the 4T was already part of Seimei 1.0 choreo, the way he executes the move here is on a whole different level of awesomeness :D (luckily in the NBC footage they filmed it from the front)  The sheer intensity of Yuzuru's gaze and the sharpness and awareness in every little gesture (I love the tiny smirks he throws around here and then).  The way he throws himself into his YOLO combo 3Alo3S, almost with a vengeance (I bet he was pissed off with himself for messing the 2nd half 4T), and how he holds onto the landing of the 3Lz out of sheer willpower and then, again, he throws himself into the sit spin without a moment of breath and then launches into the most powerful and at the same time joyful choreo sequence...(lovely arm details in the InaBauer too).  Yuzuru's determination, his will, his triumph...imo that's what makes this performance the most powerful SEIMEI he's ever done in competition, what makes this particular interpretation so strong.  He wasn't trying to portay the onmyÅji Seimei, rather, he himself was the onmyÅji, the onmyÅji Yuzuru Hanyu, the one who fights against the odds, who never surrenders and WINS. I'll always mourn that we couldn't see Seimei 2.0 skated at its full potential, with a healthy Yuzuru with stamina&training at Helsinki levels (and the layout he so strongly wanted to execute at OWG) and at top speed, like we saw in some of his practices (and a lv 4 stsq LOL), but Olympic SEIMEI is and will always be something special and unique.  Also, SEIMEI 2.0 costume is better than 1.0, so regal <3   This is why I love this performance more than the GPF one. idk if it's the same for you. Sorry for the wall text and I hope I made some sense :)

@Cory Della Vecchia That was at his first skate of Phantum of the Opera in China. He was knocked out on the ice from a collision with another skater and just laid there till finally some people came to aid him. All skaters were ordered off the Ice and he had many injuries. Stitches in his chin, clamps in his head and had abdomen, thigh, and other injuries. It caused a big up roar because there were no rules regarding injuries. American doctors came forward and treated him.He had no anesthetic as they repaired his head injury and stitches in his chin because he wanted to skate. He was not at the award ceremony and flown to a hospital in Japan. The topic of concussions came up and many athletes and others made big waves about letting him skate. The ISU changed rules regarding doctors and medical care be available at each competition.

Lando Kain they are throwing gifts (in the form of flowers and pooh bears, because Yuzuru is a fan of it) the girls collect them and they are given to the skaters after competition. Its a really old tradition

After a skater performs, its tradition in figureskating to throw gifts, flowers & plushtoys etc. by spectators. In Hanyu's case, mostly are Pooh Bear dolls as Yuzuru is a big fan of Pooh. He actually carries a Pooh tissue box for competitions. The kids are called "sweepers" or "flower kids". they are tasked to collect the gifts as there are still skaters to perform afterwards.

I can only imagine how big his fighting spirit was during this FS. He was most likely so nervous about the jumps, probably his ankle hurted, especially in the second half even he was on painkillers.. painkillers make you sleepy but he was perfectly concentrated..most of the jumps executed perfectly, very little prerotation, great take-offs and landings besides his two struggles. He must felt anxious after the two jumps just weren't going smooth, must have felt so many things at that moment. I think in that moment his fighting spirit was the greatest. Gritting his teeth, changing his next jump to a combination he hadn't tried in a long time because of the injury but still pulled it off greatly as he knew he needed this extra points..  His fighting spirit really amazes me!!!!  And then you can see all the pressure falling of after the last jump. His spirit high, his feelings exploding...for me the last 30 seconds of his FS are  one of the most emotional skating moments he ever had. That desperation, excitement, happiness, proudness and love for skating. You could feel all that especially in these 30 or so seconds.. That's why he's the greatest today. 6 quazs are fine, but this emotion, this artsy, this love for skating he expresses... it can't be compared to the other skaters...  Yuzuru Hanyu, you're more than a legendary skater, you're ar role model, an inspiration and a truly amazing person! You've worked so hard and I know you will work even harder. I'm looking forward to the future! Fighting!!!!

Yes. Hand down costs you more points though unless there is weight transfer it is not counted as a fall.
AlatarielNerwen isn't a hand down considered weight transfer and so will be called a fall and get a 1pt deduction? or does hand down only affect the GoE? tnx!

+diavol sange No, it's not always considered a weight transfer. A fall is loss of control by the skater that results in the majority of his/her body weight being supported by any other part of the body than the blades, like hand(s), knee(s). So if you just lightly touch down with your hand to steady yourself but most of your weight is still on your blades, you get big negative GOEs but no fall deduction.  Calling weight transfer can be pretty controversial sometimes. When it's very obvious there is full weight transfer they don't and the other way around but for the most part, when they just put the hand down, you don't get one.

I went and read the rulebook and I watched tons of videos and read many blogs (and then I read some research papers about physics of jumps, injuries and so on, too, LOL) to learn more about figure skating because 1) I wanted to appreciate the tech side of what Yuzuru does, even if it wasn't the reason I became his fan 2) Yuzuru loves the sport so much, so it was worth my time 3) I don't like talking about things that I don't know or understand (I think, if people want to talk about scoring and placements, they should know the rules first(*)).  As a result, I am even more amazed at what Yuzuru does on the ice and I can also appreciate other skaters more, even those who at first I didn't like that much (e.g. Patrick Chan wasn't and still isn't my cup of tea, but now I can appreciate his skating).  The downside is that you start being salty about scoring like A LOT :(    But I'm glad that thanks to Yuzuru I've come to learn so much about this wonderful sport and now I support many skaters, jr and sr and across all disciplines... tho Yuzuru is by far my absolute fave :D   Now I'm waiting for the rule changes (some of the rumours make me rather dread them, to be honest)  (*) One of my pet peeves is when some figure skating commentators call PCS "artistry".  Program componets aren't and have never been only about "artistry", not even under 6.0 system. There are and there have always been very technical things like skating skills and transitions (which one could say are the true "core" of figure skating, how blades are used all the time, not only for the big tricks) and even the more subjective components like Interpretation are rooted not in personal taste but in e.g. expression of music nuances. It's lazy and unprofessional from commentators to equate PCS to some generic and 100% subjective "artistic impression".  Whops, I used this reply to rant a little, I'm sorry :(

There are many components to the score. You have the technical elements, which is mostly jumps and how well executed they are. Yuzuruâ€™s program is one of the most difficult programs with 4 quad jumps. Performing a difficult program with a few mistakes will score you much higher than performing a easier program perfectly just on technical score alone. Then thereâ€™s the program component scores, which evaluates the skaterâ€™s general skating skills, transitions between different technical elements, interpretation of the music, general artistry, etc etc, in which Yuzuru is above the other skaters by a wide margin. He also performed close to flawless in his short program. Perhaps you should learn a bit more about figure skating before criticizing his 2 mistakes and how itâ€™s scored?

Cristina Sousa    if you don't get it, why don't you try and learn more about the sport and how it's judged? There are many good resources for beginners. Been there, done that. :) There are lots of useful blogs, ISU videos to explain scoring with actual examples, and ISU rulebooks can be downloaded for free on their site. The scoresheets of the whole competitions are there for free too, so you can see how other skaters were scored, and if you watch other skater's performances at Olympics you'll understand why Yuzuru won, fair and square. And the mistakes weren't "so many", there were only two minor flaws on landings (only step out. No hand down, no fall, no underrotation) that cost him a few points in quality of execution, as it should be. Though the mistake on 4T, which wasn't a serious mistake "per se", also cost him a consistent loss in base value because of the specific technical requirements for the free program. I could tell you more about that, but then it gets too technical.  Also, if you really want to know, in Men skating (not only senior, junior too) completely clean programs (all elements with positive grade of execution) are VERY rare. Same for Pairs, actually.  Ladies usually have cleaner programs (at least in the last group), but then you can also have events like World Championships ladies FS in Milan a few days ago, where only 2 out of 6 skaters in the last group had no negative GOE, so while top ladies USUALLY have cleaner programs than top guys, it doesn't mean they are clean ALL the time.  Figure skating is HARD. It's physically and mentally demanding.  And you have to remember, the harder the technical content (and the higher the stakes) the harder to go clean. I don't mean only harder jumps, but also everything else that happens in the program, like spins and steps.  e.g. doing lots of turns and difficult steps and one-footed skating between elements is very tiring and makes chances of mistakes higher than just skating around on two feet the whole time (apparently, when skaters' heart rates were measured, they saw they had a peak during step sequences, because of the prolonged effort. Now try and imagine doing steps during all the program, before and after jumps and spin and you'll understand it's much more physically demanding)  The current judging system tries to take all of this into account, so clean programs, while they are what all skaters aim to do and what people in the audience hope for,  aren't the only thing that matters :)

According to ä¸¡è§’æ·³ Seimei refers not only to Abeâ€Noâ€Seimei,but also to the meaning of life or soul in Japanese words. Everything living in this world has in common, all animals and plants all born on this earth will connect from the parent to the child from the past to the future. That is life, the Japanese word "Seimei".Seven years ago on March 11, there was a big earthquake in Japan Tsunami struck, tens of thousands of people died, baby to the old man was sacrificed. He was also one of the victims, the link he was practicing broke down, he was thinking of quitting figure skat. At that time, gold medalist Shizuka Arakawa of Turin Olympic women figure skat donated link repair costs. Yuzu beat Patrick Chan in the GPF 2013 prior to the Sochi Olympic, so the whole nation of Japan deemed him as their one and only gold medal hope. How do you know that Yuzu was not all over the Japanese media going into Sochi? Just because the US media hyped Nathan up, it doesn't mean that Yuzu was not hyped up by the Japanese media before Sochi. After Yuzu won the SP in the team event, beating the legend, Plushenko and Patrick Chan on the way, he became THE man to beat. Can you imagine the pressure he was under? I wouldn't say that he was under less pressure than Nathan.

To be fair, US sports media is somewhat unique in its practice of inflating expectations of young national representatives to unreachable extremes and brutally turning on those young national representatives when they inevitably fail to meet those impossible standards.

Hi Caeser, welcome to the World of Figure Skating. Yuzuru skated in the Olympics with an injured right ankle & he had minimum training days coming into the Olympics. The only recovered 30% from his injury when he won the Gold. Itâ€™s take great courage & amazing strength to come up with a Free Skate of this level & near perfection. In addition to that, he was 1st in the Short Program. The Gold is determined by combining scores from both the Short Program & Free Skate. He is currently the World Record holder in Menâ€™s Figure Skating for all categories. Do watch his performances over the last few years & you will soon understand why we regard him as the best.

Hi, Yu! No one in the top 6 or so went completely clean in this free program. The short program was a different matter though, because the top three didn't make mistakes and Hanyu's score was an  Olympic record (please watch it, it's amazing). It's all about the cumulative score between short program and free program such as this one. Anyway, to answer your question, yes, his jump technique is textbook. The quads he jumped in this program may not be the most difficult, but overall this program is still one of the most complex ones ever and certainly the most difficult in the top 6 right now. He has the least amount of crossovers and the highest amount of one-foot skating, as well as the most difficult transitions into his jumps. His spins are gorgeous and well-centered and has accompanying hand movements and speed (especially in his SP and exhibitions). So yeah, his musicality is innate and ever-present in this performance when every note and beat of the drum is not wasted. Not only is his technique at high level but also his components such as skating skills, interpretation of music, performance, composition, and like I mentioned, transitions. His performance of the same program from NHK 2015 and GPF 2015 did not have mistakes, but personally, this one is more special and emotional because it's on Olympic ice--where the stakes are higher than ever and he did this while on painkillers since his right ankle was and still is injured from an accident in November. Personally, I think the greatest men's skate of all time was Yuzuru's Hope and Legacy from Worlds 2017, followed by this one. I hope this answers your question :)

Your comment is quite ignorant concerning the American female skaters. Karen and Bradie are only 18 and 20, respectively, and are just getting started. This was their first Olympics. Bradie has been training since the age of 2. She improved upon her 9th finish at the Olympics and just got 6th at Worlds in March. She has ascended from junior to senior level rapidly and no one expected her to win US Nationals, which she did with aplomb. She was never going to medal at the Olympics, of course. She did help the team get bronze with a solid performance in the team event. And Karen Chen placed 4th at 2017 Worlds, and is the reason the US even got 3 slots at the Olympics. Mirai laid down a triple axel at Pyeongchang, the first American woman to do so at the Olympics. So of course they can compete with the current world standard. But if you want to emulate the Russian system of lining up girls like a factory assembly line, abusing and starving them and throwing them out as soon as they hit puberty and have no chance at gold as Eteri does, then go ahead and admire that. Alina Zagitova, the gold medal winner, had a dismal showing at Worlds, only a couple of months after the Olympics. She is only 15, but I fear the end is near for her, just like it was for Julia Lipnitskaya of Sochi fame. Never hear about her anymore, do you? That's because she was used and tossed aside like all the others.

its okay. Its been tradition in figure skating for a long time ğŸ˜ the sweepers or called as flower kids will collect them and the organizers will give them to the skaters. It also depends on the organizers of the event if they allow gifts to be thrown (e.g. skate Canada AC - they don't allow gifts to be thrown on the ice). in Hanyu's case or other skaters who get massive gifts,  they will donate them to people in need like kids or local hospitals as they can't bring them all anymore (hello excess baggage) back home to their country. judges adjust their score after the actual performance is finished because they can review elements and such

after a skater performs, judges makes final review of the elements he made like the jumps (his final jumps were not perfect tho), spins and steps, In simpler sense if they were perfectly executed, they add more points (GOE), if some were slightly bad, they deduct points.
