It's done by the same choreographer but if you compare SEIMEI version 1 in the 2015-2016 season, you can see the small touches that sharpens the programme, e.g. the choreo sequence looks even sharper. He didn't do the biellmann spin here in order to preserve his energy (he usually did that if he did not feel well enough). Of course the layout/component is a bit different with the 4th quad added (the 4T in the second half is a planned 4TLo3S but he missed it. That's why he changed his 3A2T to 3ALo3S).

Yuzuru Hanyu has shown over and over again that he is very dedicated to this sport. He always gives his best despite the huge pressure put on him and the numerous injuries he has suffered over the years(those who accuse him with being inconsistent should go to his wiki page look at all the unfortunate things he has gone through and honestly tell us if they could have done better than Hanyu at those conditions). Like it or not he is the most complete skater out there at the moment. He came to the Olympics after 2 months of rehabilitations with only 3 weeks of practice(only 2 weeks of jumping quads), his ankle was not healed at all and he skated while taking painkillers. He probably worsened his condition by competing at the Olympics but he did it for himself and for his country. The fact that he has to rest for 3-4 months after the Olympics shows how serious his injury really is. This guy is a fighter nothing can change that or the history he has made. He deserved this medal, like he said he put his life at stake to win it.

Chen has the firepower but not the finesse nor control required to combine his technical firepower into a cohesive performance, which is why his artistry isn't so visible during competition, and it is why even his best scores do not come up to what Hanyu and Fernandez scored in past competitions with less firepower, even with the judges giving him generous GOEs and PCS despite the fact. Hanyu and Fernandez lose to him BV wise but max GOE and high PCS are something Chen still needs to be able to convince ALL the judges to give him, starting with him showing them that he's actually earning what he's getting now at some point, for him to outscore the other two. So, skill-wise, Chen is still behind these two. But skill is something that can be gained with enough dedication and the required mindset.  But skill isn't the only thing he is lacking. Competing isn't simply about skill. It's a combination of the ability to control your nerves while withstanding the pressure and at same time put forth your very best. It's easier to do good when you're unfettered by pressure but a different story when you have to juggle that along with everything else. IF Chen had the nerves required on top of skating clean, he would have had a good chance of winning, but only IF both Hanyu and Fernandez, and perhaps even Uno, all make mistakes. And that's the best what if scenario I think we can settle with.

Â @thewizardofozziver2830Â , I think some comments at the top mentioned it already? But FYI he fractured his right ankle ligaments 3 months prior to the Olympics, and we have to remember that since the majority of skaters, including Yuzuru, rotate counterclockwise, they land their jumps on their right foot. Yuzuru had quadruple jumps in this program, which means his right ankle, still injured, had to hold out under a lot of stress. When a skater lands a quadruple, their foot has to bear 4-8 times of their own weight. Yuzuru was on painkillers, but he explained later in an interview that the medications didn't really work, as he still felt pain during his skate.  But it's not the first or last time he's skated on crippling injuries, unfortunately. Just to name a few, Yuzu has been injured at every world championship except for 2017 (but he had an asthma attack before it;) he also had a crash with another skater at CoC 2014, and he carried that injury into the following NHK and GPF, which were both less than a month after it. But he has persevered through it all, through disaster and injury. He's an inspiration to many of us, and I think his many experiences have made him who he is.
